    language: "english",
    text: "The practice of meditation, which encompasses a diverse range of mental training techniques developed across different cultural and religious traditions including Buddhism, Hinduism, Christianity, Judaism, and Islam, as well as contemporary secular applications developed for clinical, therapeutic, and performance enhancement purposes, has attracted increasing scientific attention in recent decades as researchers have sought to understand the neurobiological mechanisms through which contemplative practice produces its well-documented effects on attention, emotion, stress physiology, and well-being. Mindfulness meditation, which involves the deliberate direction of attention to present-moment experience with an attitude of curiosity, openness, and non-judgmental acceptance rather than the habitual evaluation, elaboration, and narrative construction that characterizes ordinary thinking, has been the subject of more than a thousand published scientific studies since Jon Kabat-Zinn developed Mindfulness-Based Stress Reduction as a clinical program in the late nineteen seventies, with research demonstrating significant benefits for conditions including depression, anxiety, chronic pain, stress, and attentional difficulties. Neuroimaging studies have revealed that long-term meditation practice is associated with structural and functional changes in brain regions including the prefrontal cortex, anterior cingulate cortex, insula, and amygdala that are involved in attention regulation, emotional processing, self-awareness, and stress response, providing biological evidence for the cognitive and emotional changes reported by experienced meditators. The growing evidence for the benefits of contemplative practice has led to its incorporation into educational programs for children and adolescents, occupational health and wellness programs for adults, criminal justice rehabilitation programs, and healthcare settings ranging from pain management clinics to oncology departments where helping patients cope with the psychological dimensions of serious illness is a recognized priority."
